r own. There’s a mint-channel I can whisper you through if you choose the quieter way; it runs behind a wax-bark copse where fenwives are said to pluck vows like fruit, and if you keep a promise in your mouth you can’t be led by theirs. Keep your lamp low, count the names, and if the Ford sings wrong again, remember that a wrong song sometimes comes from a throat choked by someone else’s hand; free the choke and the voice comes back.\"}\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"M1-C1\", \"title\": \"Ring the flood-bells early and loud\", \"text\": \"You order the flood-bells tested in full voice at the Chainbridge Piers and again as the convoy noses into the first shallows, a warning to any hand that thinks mist can make a mask of law. You stand high on a crate of grain and shout the river-rights for all to hear, a litany of names and crossings that even the fog must respect, and you let House Kelvar’s watchers across the way know you do not intend to be quietly trimmed. The crew breathes easier as the tones braid with the river’s own harmonies, and you see shoulders drop as if a weight has slid back into the water where it belongs. Rook’s bell rings true, and the sound turns the dark into a place where errors must name themselves before they move, and that makes ghosts and men alike think twice. You know it risks spooking honest reedcutters and can draw the attention of anyone itching for a loud excuse, but a bold chord now might clear the waterway of hands that prefer the soft theft that breeds feuds later.\", \"outcome\": \"The early peals ripple down the Ford like bright stones across a drum and scatter a pair of masked cutters who melt back into the reeds, deciding this won’t be a quiet pluck; a length of towline later turns up nicked but unsevered, proof that a blade hesitated. House Kelvar’s toll-tower clerk appears on a balcony with a ledger and a squint, but he closes the book when the bell names the Covenant’s right of passage at dusk under flood-watch, and his guards lean their spears where the iron learns to nap. The convoy passes the first teeth without a snag, and the crew’s finger-tap chatter settles into workman rhythm, though one echo in the bell’s fade carries a strange dissonance that your prism-lamp catches as an off-beat code. Mara’s trust in you deepens when your report reaches her, and she notes that sometimes loud mercy prevents loud war, but she warns the bell costs goodwill with those who think you peacocked on the river’s stage. Your choice wins space and time, and yet a distant, softer bell answers from somewhere behind the reeds, as if someone has learned your chord and intends to test your ear for it again.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"M1-C2\", \"title\": \"Parley with the masked reedcutters at oar’s length\", \"text\": \"You call for oars and slack, bring the barges to a cautious drift, and raise your empty hands so lantern-light fills your palms instead of steel, showing that you mean to trade words before blows. You ask the river for silence and get it, a hush like a held breath across slate teeth, and in that space you invite the masked cutters to step into the lamp’s ring and name their price and grievance. You speak the old river customs—that no rope should be cut on a bread-barge, that grain runs first in lean months, that a mistaken hand can make amends with labor instead of blood—and you offer a rite-offering of work-ropes and fresh hooks rather than coin that would be read as toll. You let them see the Pilots’ seal on your copper ward-tile, not as a threat but as a reminder that law and water both bend when spoken to carefully, and that you, too, have cut peat and paid with blisters. Behind your words is your stance, the set of your feet like anchors in the deck, and the way your crew watches you with trust that can’t be counterfeited; your parley is a plank you lay between boats so no one falls in.\", \"outcome\": \"Two figures rise from the reed-curtain with knives held low and pa